push the two pieces together,

5
00:00:10,620 --> 00:00:11,453
and it'll become,

6
00:00:11,453 --> 00:00:14,370
once again, one single piece.

7
00:00:14,370 --> 00:00:15,577
At first, you might think,

8
00:00:15,577 --> 00:00:17,497
"Well, that's not so unusual,

9
00:00:17,497 --> 00:00:19,567
"like, if I took a strip of Blu Tack

10
00:00:19,567 --> 00:00:21,097
"and slice that into two pieces,

11
00:00:21,097 --> 00:00:23,107
"and then press those two pieces together,

12
00:00:23,107 --> 00:00:23,977
"I would, once again,

13
00:00:23,977 --> 00:00:26,550
"have a single piece of Blu Tack."

14
00:00:26,550 --> 00:00:27,383
You might also say,

15
00:00:27,383 --> 00:00:29,347
"Look, if I have two droplets of water,

16
00:00:29,347 --> 00:00:30,217
"and I push them together,

17
00:00:30,217 --> 00:00:32,549
"they become a single droplet of water."

18
00:00:32,549 --> 00:00:33,990
The difference between Blu Tack

19
00:00:33,990 --> 00:00:35,340
and this self-healing polymer

20
00:00:35,340 --> 00:00:36,330
is that, well,

21
00:00:36,330 --> 00:00:38,130
Blu Tack is sticky,

22
00:00:38,130 --> 00:00:39,210
it sticks to my hand,

23
00:00:39,210 --> 00:00:40,590
it sticks to a wall,

24
00:00:40,590 --> 00:00:42,630
it sticks to the back of this picture

25
00:00:42,630 --> 00:00:44,100
of Patrick Stewart.

26
00:00:44,100 --> 00:00:45,690
So, it's not surprising

27
00:00:45,690 --> 00:00:48,180
that Blu Tack sticks to itself,

28
00:00:48,180 --> 00:00:51,060
but this polymer isn't sticky.

29
00:00:51,060 --> 00:00:52,860
The same goes for droplets of water,

30
00:00:52,860 --> 00:00:55,380
they're sticky and they flow,

31
00:00:55,380 --> 00:00:56,640
because they're a liquid,

32
00:00:56,640 --> 00:00:59,880
so, we should naturally
expect different behavior

33
00:00:59,880 --> 00:01:01,290
from droplets of water,

34
00:01:01,290 --> 00:01:04,140
as we do from a strip of polymer.

35
00:01:04,140 --> 00:01:06,240
We can actually flip this
question on its head,

36
00:01:06,240 --> 00:01:07,297
instead of saying,

37
00:01:07,297 --> 00:01:09,180
"Why is this polymer self-healing?"

38
00:01:09,180 --> 00:01:10,013
We can say,

39
00:01:10,013 --> 00:01:12,427
"Why aren't other things self-healing?

40
00:01:12,427 --> 00:01:14,190
"Why isn't metal self-healing?"

41
00:01:14,190 --> 00:01:16,890
Like, if I cut this piece of metal in two,

42
00:01:16,890 --> 00:01:20,040
why is it that I can't just
push the two ends together,

43
00:01:20,040 --> 00:01:23,160
and it fuses back into
a single piece of metal?

44
00:01:23,160 --> 00:01:24,750
Like, if you think about what's happening

45
00:01:24,750 --> 00:01:26,610
at the molecular level,

46
00:01:26,610 --> 00:01:30,240
a metal is a lattice of ions

47
00:01:30,240 --> 00:01:34,530
in a cloud of mobile electrons.

48
00:01:34,530 --> 00:01:37,740
So, if you slice this lattice in two,

49
00:01:37,740 --> 00:01:40,560
and bring those two ends back together,

50
00:01:40,560 --> 00:01:41,430
well, (chuckles) to me,

51
00:01:41,430 --> 00:01:44,340
that looks like a single metal lattice,

52
00:01:44,340 --> 00:01:46,800
so, why doesn't it become one?

53
00:01:46,800 --> 00:01:47,670
In the case of metal,

54
00:01:47,670 --> 00:01:49,650
the answer's actually
quite straightforward,

55
00:01:49,650 --> 00:01:51,090
it's oxidation.

56
00:01:51,090 --> 00:01:53,010
I've got some sodium metal here,

57
00:01:53,010 --> 00:01:55,230
which is soft enough to cut with a knife,

58
00:01:55,230 --> 00:01:56,190
and when I do,

59
00:01:56,190 --> 00:01:59,160
you can see it's actually
a really shiny metal,

60
00:01:59,160 --> 00:02:00,750
but that doesn't last forever,

61
00:02:00,750 --> 00:02:01,920
it doesn't take long

62
00:02:01,920 --> 00:02:05,460
for that shiny surface to
become dull in appearance.

63
00:02:05,460 --> 00:02:07,380
That's because the metal is reacting

64
00:02:07,380 --> 00:02:09,419
with oxygen in the air.

65
00:02:09,419 --> 00:02:10,679
Actually, the same thing happens

66
00:02:10,680 --> 00:02:12,180
when you cut any metal,

67
00:02:12,180 --> 00:02:15,240
it's just that that oxidation
layer isn't as visible

68
00:02:15,240 --> 00:02:17,430
in the case of, say, steel,

69
00:02:17,430 --> 00:02:19,290
as compared to sodium.

70
00:02:19,290 --> 00:02:20,790
So, it's understandable then

71
00:02:20,790 --> 00:02:22,680
that if you took two pieces of metal

72
00:02:22,680 --> 00:02:24,030
and pushed them together,

73
00:02:24,030 --> 00:02:26,820
they wouldn't form one
single piece of metal,

74
00:02:26,820 --> 00:02:29,370
because there is a layer of oxidized metal

75
00:02:29,370 --> 00:02:30,780
in between.

76
00:02:30,780 --> 00:02:33,510
In fact, if you were
to cut a piece of metal

77
00:02:33,510 --> 00:02:35,250
in the vacuum of space,

78
00:02:35,250 --> 00:02:38,310
and then push those cut surfaces together,

79
00:02:38,310 --> 00:02:40,680
they would fuse together.

80
00:02:40,680 --> 00:02:41,513
We know this,

81
00:02:41,513 --> 00:02:43,440
because it's happened in situations

82
00:02:43,440 --> 00:02:45,390
when we don't want it to happen,

83
00:02:45,390 --> 00:02:46,770
at least, once.

84
00:02:46,770 --> 00:02:48,210
In April, 1991,

85
00:02:48,210 --> 00:02:50,100
the Galileo spacecraft

86
00:02:50,100 --> 00:02:53,040
was supposed to open
its high-gain antenna,

87
00:02:53,040 --> 00:02:54,450
looks a bit like an umbrella,

88
00:02:54,450 --> 00:02:56,670
but three ribs of that umbrella

89
00:02:56,670 --> 00:03:00,030
had cold welded to the
body of the spacecraft,

90
00:03:00,030 --> 00:03:01,620
and so, it couldn't open.

91
00:03:01,620 --> 00:03:02,820
This stuff is a bit different

92
00:03:02,820 --> 00:03:04,440
to a metal, though,

93
00:03:04,440 --> 00:03:05,700
because it's a polymer,

94
00:03:05,700 --> 00:03:08,910
so, it would be more like
if I cut a piece of plastic

95
00:03:08,910 --> 00:03:10,200
into two pieces,

96
00:03:10,200 --> 00:03:12,750
and then try to push
those two pieces together.

97
00:03:12,750 --> 00:03:13,770
In this case, clearly,

98
00:03:13,770 --> 00:03:15,540
they don't fuse back together.

99
00:03:15,540 --> 00:03:16,950
And I suppose that makes sense,

100
00:03:16,950 --> 00:03:19,080
like, if you're cutting
a piece of plastic in two

101
00:03:19,080 --> 00:03:22,470
then you're cutting through
individual polymer chains,

102
00:03:22,470 --> 00:03:25,320
you're breaking bonds
between carbon atoms.

103
00:03:25,320 --> 00:03:27,000
When you break a covalent bond like this,

104
00:03:27,000 --> 00:03:28,590
you're left with radicals,

105
00:03:28,590 --> 00:03:31,620
that's atoms that have
unpaired valence electrons,

106
00:03:31,620 --> 00:03:32,880
they're incredibly reactive,

107
00:03:32,880 --> 00:03:36,270
so, we should expect the
exposed surface atoms

108
00:03:36,270 --> 00:03:40,050
to react with molecules in the atmosphere,

109
00:03:40,050 --> 00:03:41,790
or if it was in a vacuum,

110
00:03:41,790 --> 00:03:45,870
I imagine, they would react
with the atoms around them

111
00:03:45,870 --> 00:03:47,850
in the substance itself,

112
00:03:47,850 --> 00:03:51,810
and so, that exposed
surface becomes unreactive.

113
00:03:51,810 --> 00:03:53,310
It's not sticky anymore.

114
00:03:53,310 --> 00:03:55,620
If you press those two surfaces together,

115
00:03:55,620 --> 00:03:58,230
those bonds aren't going to reform,

116
00:03:58,230 --> 00:04:02,160
unless you can introduce quite
a high activation energy.

117
00:04:02,160 --> 00:04:05,070
So, why is it then that
I can cut this material

118
00:04:05,070 --> 00:04:06,270
into two pieces,

119
00:04:06,270 --> 00:04:07,800
push the two pieces together,

120
